            <person xml:id="pers0167">
               <p>Born in <placeName>Winslow, Buckinghamshire</placeName>, Biggs served as butler to
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1318.xml"/>Sir James Lowther</persName>
                     (<date from="1673" to="1755">1673–1755</date>), and was included in
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1318.xml"/>Lowther</persName>&apos;s
                  will. He came under Methodist preaching in <date when="1750">1750</date> and was
                  converted. While never listed in the Minutes, he traveled with <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg>
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1483.xml"/>John Murlin</persName> in the late
                     <date>1750s</date>. He was part of the perfectionist group that gathered around
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0134.xml"/>George Bell</persName> in
                     <date when="1760">1760</date>, and departed Methodism with <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0134.xml"/>Bell</persName> in <date when="1763"
                     >1763</date>. Cf. his autobiographical letter to <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> of <date when="1759-12"
                     >December 1759</date>, <hi rend="italic">AM</hi> 3 (<date when="1780"
                     >1780</date>): 493–96.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
